<HEADLINE>
<P>
U-T LABOR TALKS END WITHOUT ACCORD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PATRICK McDONNELL, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Representatives of the San Diego Newspaper Guild and the Union-Tribune 
Publishing Co., attempting to resolve an increasingly acrimonious labor dispute 
threatening the two daily newspapers, ended talks Friday without agreement 
after a full day of negotiating. 
</P>
<P>
No date was set for new talks, although both sides expressed hope that some 
sessions could be held next week. 
</P>
<P>
The lack of an agreement, despite the presence of a state mediator, appeared to 
worsen an already grim mood among employees. After Friday's negotiating 
session, workers held a boisterous meeting at their strike headquarters. 
</P>
<P>
"People in the plant are just outraged with management," said James Griffin, an 
international representative of the Newspaper Guild who participated in the 
negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
"This is a sad day for San Diego journalism," one guild member said after the 
talks ended. 
</P>
<P>
Guild officials accused management of refusing to budge from its position on 
two critical issues: The length of a new contract and the use of company 
vehicles by circulation employees. The guild is seeking a three-year contract, 
while management has offered a one-year package. The company is seeking to cut 
back on use of fleet vehicles, the guild says. 
</P>
<P>
Herb Klein, editor-in-chief of Copley Press, which publishes the morning Union 
and afternoon Tribune, said both sides had made various proposals, but he 
acknowledged that advances were few. 
</P>
<P>
"I'm disappointed that there wasn't as much progress as I had hoped," Klein 
said. 
</P>
<P>
The two sides, working with the state mediator relaying proposals from room to 
room, met from 9:30 a.m. to 7 p.m. at the Hyatt Islandia hotel. One minor 
matter, involving leaves of absence, was resolved, Griffin said. 
</P>
<P>
The guild's 1,150 members, including reporters, photographers and employees in 
the advertising, circulation, library and maintenance departments, have been 
without a contract for 18 months. The guild authorized a strike last month. 
</P>
<P>
Talks had resumed Wednesday after a 12-day hiatus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
