<P>
FEW CANCEL DELTA FLIGHTS AFTER THREAT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Delta Air Lines said that it had received few cancellations since it disclosed 
a threat against its transatlantic operations. 
</P>
<P>
The airline said that only four dozen of 5,000 customers with reservations for 
transatlantic flights had canceled trips. Delta announced Thursday that it had 
received a telephone threat at its Dublin, Ireland, sales office, but the 
caller did not specify a flight, date or city. The airline said it notified the 
Federal Aviation Administration and took steps to increase security but that it 
believes the threat is a hoax. Delta flies to eight European cities from six 
U.S. airports, including Los Angeles International. 
</P>
</TEXT>
