<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWSWIRE: JUDGE RECOMMENDS PROBERT DEPORTATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A federal immigration judge in Chicago recommended that Bob Probert, former 
Detroit Red Wing, be deported for his conviction on a drug importation charge, 
an attorney for the hockey player said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
Probert is currently serving a three-month term at a federal prison in 
Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
After his release, Probert is scheduled to spend three months at a halfway 
house designated by federal court. 
</P>
<P>
Probert's attorney, Harold Fried, said he will spend the weekend reviewing 
Probert's options, including an appeal. 
</P>
<P>
Probert was arrested March 2 at the tunnel connecting Windsor, Canada, and 
Detroit when authorities found cocaine in his underwear. 
</P>
<P>
He pleaded guilty in U.S. District Court in Detroit to importing cocaine for 
his own use and was sentenced Oct. 17 to three months in prison, three months 
in a halfway house and three years' probation. 
</P>
<P>
Two days after his arrest, Probert was banned from the NHL. League president 
John Ziegler later said Probert would be allowed to rejoin the Red Wings if he 
fulfilled all terms of his probation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
