<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: LA HABRA; 
</P>
<P>
OFFICIALS DISCUSS IMPROVING HIGHWAY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAVID F. BURKE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
City officials this week discussed developing Imperial Highway into a "super 
street," with improvements designed to help traffic flow in the city, which has 
no freeways. 
</P>
<P>
Tom Fortune, Orange County Transportation Commission public affairs officer, 
said a super street is "something less than a freeway but the most efficient 
surface street possible." 
</P>
<P>
Possible improvements from Beach Boulevard to Santa Ana Canyon Road include 
widening of the highway, addition or improvements to signals, construction of 
bus turnouts, consolidation of driveways and removal of on-street parking, 
Fortune said. 
</P>
<P>
The council also appointed Mayor Beth Graham to act as liaison in the planning 
process that is expected to be completed by September. 
</P>
<P>
If the project is approved, construction is expected to begin sometime in 1992. 
DAVID F. BURKE 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
LA HABRA (CA) -- TRANSPORTATION; TRAFFIC MANAGEMENT; STREETS 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA010690-0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 158953 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
January 6, 1990, Saturday, Orange County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 3; Column 1; Metro Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
200 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: PLACENTIA; 
</P>
<P>
OFFICE PROJECT OKD FOR PUBLISHING FIRM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JULIE ESPY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Construction of an office building on a piece of prime commercial property will 
begin in March despite arguments by some city officials that the parcel should 
be used for other purposes. 
</P>
<P>
The council passed ordinances this week paving the way for McMullen Publishing 
to build a new office building on Placentia Avenue adjacent to Brian Chuchua's 
Jeep Inc. 
</P>
<P>
"This is a welcome addition for the city," said Peter Gustaf, attorney for both 
McMullen Publishing and Brian Chuchua's Jeep. "Their organization will be a 
real plus factor for the city." 
</P>
<P>
City Councilwoman Maria Moreno said she favors the site but had long considered 
the spot to be ideal for senior housing. 
</P>
<P>
"In all honesty, I am disappointed that we couldn't see a business that would 
provide a service for the people," Moreno said. 
</P>
<P>
The office building will occupy space now used by the auto dealership as a 
helicopter landing pad. McMullen Publishing, which publishes automotive 
magazines, will employ architecture called "different" and "modern" by Joyce 
Rosenthal, director of development services. 
</P>
<P>
"It's something we haven't seen before in Placentia," Rosenthal said. "It will 
be a very good-looking building." JULIE ESPY 
</P>
</TEXT>
